</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="1300">5. Redistributing stock with the plentymarkets app</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>You can also redistribute stock using the plentymarkets app. Refer to the <a href="/en/app/functions/warehouse-management/receiving-rebooking">Receiving goods and redistributing stock</a> page of the manual to learn how it’s done and which settings you’ll need to configure in advance.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="600">6. Searching variations that are below or have reached the reorder level</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>A good reason to manage stocks in your system is that it allows you to reorder variations from your supplier early enough so you do not run out of stock. The reorder level is your reference figure to define a stock level at which reordering in time is still possible. To filter variations that have reached the reorder level, proceed as follows.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Filtering variations by reorder level:</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Searching stocks:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Go to <strong>Stock » Stocks</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Select a <strong>Supplier</strong> from the drop-down list.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Select the option <strong>Reorder level reached/below</strong> in the <strong>limitation</strong> filter.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on <strong>Search</strong> (<span class="icon blue"><i class="fa fa-search  "></i></span>). <br>
→ The variations that are below or have reached the reorder level will be listed.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>When you have listed the variations, you can directly create a reorder in this menu.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="700">7. Reordering variations that are below or have reached the reorder level</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>To reorder the variations that you have just listed, proceed as follows.</p>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock warning">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-warning" title="Warning"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Click on reorder before switching pages</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>When you switch to another page, the entered quantities will be reset. This is why you need to click on reorder before you switch the page. As long as the reorder is still open, further variations will be added to the reorder.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Creating reorders:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Go to <strong>Stock » Stocks</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Filter by reorder level as described above.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on <strong>Accept suggestion</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>If a suggestion does not seem right to you, enter the <strong>quantity</strong> that you wish to order.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on <strong>Create reorder</strong>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock important">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-important" title="Important"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Create reorder is not visible</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>If you cannot see the <strong>Create order</strong> button, check that <strong>Yes</strong> is set for the <strong>order</strong> filter on the left. The filter has to be set to yes. Otherwise reorders cannot be carried out.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Go to <strong>Stock » Reorder management » Reorders</strong> to see the reorder that was just created. The reorder receives the status <strong>Open</strong>. Further variations that you want to order from the same supplier will be added to the same reorder as long as you have a reorder that is open.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="750">8. Working without reorder level</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>You can decide whether you want to define a reorder level for your items and thus receive reorder suggestions. If you don’t want to do so, it is not necessary to define a value for the reorder level in the <strong>Warehouse</strong> tab. In this case, proceed as follows:</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Working without reorder level:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Go to <strong>Item » Edit item » [select item] » tab: Warehouse</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>In the <strong>Reorder level</strong> field, delete the default value <code>0</code>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Save</strong> (<span class="icon green"><i class="fa fa-save  "></i></span>) the settings.<br>
→ No reorder level will be specified for this item.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>In case you have defined several warehouses for this variation in the <strong>Warehouse</strong> tab, enter the value <code>0</code> for each warehouse in the <strong>Reorder level</strong> field. Here you can also define whether you want to activate (define a value) the reorder level for a variation in a specific warehouse, but deactivate (do not define a value) it in other warehouses.<br>
If you want to delete the value for several variations, use the import type <strong>Item</strong>. In the mapping, select the field <strong>Warehouse/Reorder level</strong> as target field and activate it via the toggle button on the left. By doing so, the respective column in the CSV file will be empty.</p>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock note">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-note" title="Note"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Use reorder level for main variation only</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>If you want to use the reorder level for a main variation but not for a side variation, you need to deactivate the inheritance on the side variation. Otherwise, the reorder level of the main variation will be used for the side variation, too.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="800">9. Checking reserved stock</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Booking out variations is crucial for managing stocks correctly. If you note that reserved stock exists for a variation or that more stock is reserved than should be and you know for sure that all orders have been shipped, you can search for orders that have not been booked out. Stock remains reserved until you booked out the variations. This means that the order status does not influence whether or not stock is reserved. The important step is to actually book the variations out.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Our recommended course of action that many users follow is to first book out the variations and to use this action to set the order to status 7. Use status 7 to display all orders that are in status 7 but that have not been booked out correctly.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Searching for outgoing items that were not booked yet:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Go to <strong>Orders » Edit orders</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>In the <strong>Filter</strong> tab, select <strong>[7] Outgoing items booked</strong> for the <strong>= Status</strong> option in order to select all processed orders.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Select the filter <strong>Outgoing items</strong> and set the option <strong>not booked</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Click on <strong>Search</strong> (<span class="icon blue"><i class="fa fa-search  "></i></span>) to carry out the search.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>If there are still orders in status 7 for which the outgoing items were not booked yet, you will receive an overview of them with this search filter and you can decide individually how to proceed with these orders.</p>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock important">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-important" title="Important"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Automatic stock update: Changes to the order status</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The automatic stock update works in such a way that certain orders are automatically moved to another status.<br>
<strong>Example</strong>: For orders in status 4 it is checked whether there is stock available. If that is the case and the user has activated the option in the order settings, they are automatically moved to status 5. In the <strong>Stock » Stocks</strong> menu you can find the respective buttons <strong>Recalculate stocks</strong> and <strong>Order status 4 or 5 - calculate</strong>.
<strong>Automatic stock update (b)</strong> means that the stocks have been recalculated and <strong>automatic stock update (m)</strong> means that the order status 4 or 5 has been calculated.
If you want to avoid that an order with stock is automatically moved to status 5, you should not use status 4.
For further info on the order status see <a href="/en/orders/managing-orders#1200">here</a>.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="900">10. Releasing reserved stocks</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>If you or your customer cancel an order, the stock that was reserved for that order can be released again. You can only create a cancellation as long as no variations have been booked out. In case variations have already been booked out and the order is about to be shipped or has already been delivered to your customer you need to create a return. The stock calculation is not based on order statuses but on events and actions. This means if the status of an order changes, the stock will not automatically be released.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>However, you can still define a status for cancelled orders and use this status to release stock. Define the status for cancellations. Status 8 is commonly used for cancellations. If you use a status other than [8] for cancellations or if you use the additional status options 8.1, 8.2 etc., you can determine this status or even a whole range of statuses in which orders are considered to be cancelled.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Editing basic settings for the status of cancelled orders:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Go to <strong>Setup » Orders » Settings</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Select the status range that you wish to use for cancellations from the two drop-down lists under <strong>Status of cancelled orders</strong>. The drop-down lists are <strong>from</strong> and <strong>to</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Save</strong> (<span class="icon green"><i class="fa fa-save  "></i></span>) the settings.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="950">11. Importing negative stock</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>With imports of the type <strong>Item</strong>, <strong>Stock</strong> or <strong>Incoming items</strong> you can import negative stock. This is useful if you notice a difference in your stock after inspecting your inventory or if less items were delivered than you actually ordered.
When using the import types Item and Stock, the values from the CSV file or from the Own value are imported 1:1.
When using the import type Incoming items, however, the values are subtracted from the stock.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Importing negative stock:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Go to <strong>Data » Import</strong>.<br>
→ The import overview opens.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Select an import. The import has to be of the type Item, Stock or Incoming items (warehouse, storage location and quantity are mandatory fields).<br>
<span class="icon "><i class="fa fa-map-signs  "></i></span> <strong><em>Or</em></strong>: Click on <strong>Add import</strong> in order to add an import of the type Item, Stock or Incoming items. For further information, refer to the <a href="/en/data/importing-data/ElasticSync#1210">Using the import tool</a> page.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Switch to the <strong>Mapping</strong> tab.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>In the field <strong>Source</strong>, select the option <strong>Own value</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>In the field <strong>Value</strong>, enter the negative stock (e.g. -25).</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Save</strong> (<span class="icon green"><i class="fa fa-save  "></i></span>) the settings.<br>
→ The negative stock is imported.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="1000">12. Exporting or importing stock data</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>You can export or import stock data and this way you can let your system know about the latest stocktaking that you carried out. The data format <a href="/en/data/export-import/data-formats/stock">Stock</a> contains the relevant stock data from your system. Data formats that might generally be useful when working with stock are:</p>
</div>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p><a href="/en/data/export-import/data-formats/stock">Stock</a>,</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><a href="/en/data/export-import/data-formats/variationsupplier">VariationSupplier</a>,</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><a href="/en/data/export-import/data-formats/variationwarehouse">VariationWarehouse</a> and</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><a href="/en/data/export-import/data-formats/warehouse">Warehouse</a></p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>All data formats available in plentymarkets as well as a general description on how to export or import data from or into plentymarkets can be found on the <a href="/en/data">data</a> manual page.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="1100">13. Viewing the stock movements history</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>You can view a variation’s stock movements in the <strong>Stock movement</strong> tab of the variation. You can open the <strong>stock movements</strong> by either opening the variation or by clicking on the physical stock of one of the results in the stock results list. This tab shows you how your stock reached its current level. In other words, you will see the different bookings that led to the current result. This will increase transparency of your stock management and in addition it enables you to understand your bookings later. <br>
Item bundles do not have an own stock movements tab, because the stock of bundles is calculated from the stock of the bundle components.</p>
</div>
<div class="imageblock">
<div class="content">
<img src="{{plugin_path('PlentyManual')}}/images/stock-management/assets/EN-Managing-stocks-01.png" alt="EN Managing stocks 01">
</div>
<div class="title">Figure 1. Opening stock movements</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph instruction">
<p>Opening the stock movement tab:</p>
</div>
<div class="olist arabic">
<ol class="arabic">
<li>
<p>Go to <strong>Stock » Stocks</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>In the results list, click on the <strong>quantity</strong> displayed in the <strong>PS</strong> (physical stock) column (image 1, red arrow) of the variation that you wish to open. <br>
→ The <strong>Stock movements</strong> tab within the <strong>Stock</strong> tab of the item opens.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
</div><div class="sect1">
<h2 id="1200">14. Making automatic processes dependent on stock</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>For example, the item’s display in the online store can depend on its stock: If the item can be delivered, it is offered in the online store. As soon as the net stock is 0, the item is no longer displayed. Furthermore listings can depend on stock. This is a way to avoid overselling. You can choose your hood and ricardo settings to end listings if the stock is low. You can also choose to end eBay listings if the stock is low, but in addition you can choose to automatically relist eBay listings if stock has increased. To get a more detailed description of the settings, open the <a href="/en/markets/ebay/ebay-setup#11000">eBay listings</a> page.</p>
</div>
</div>
